All better, she thought...<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Qeynos, the &quot;enlightened city&quot;. Paladins, monks, clerics chanting of the goods of their gods and how to serve. Heralds shouting news in the streets. <br>
<br>
Vendors sold wares of varying quality, from the barely adequate to the immensely valuable. Kings and Queens carry sway here and with monarchy came court and politics. <br>
<br>
And with court and politics invariably came corruption. The Unseen Hands, the well known Corrupt guards. The beauty and lawful splendor of the city lended itself well to the polarity of hate and greed. <br>
<br>
A confusing town, thought Xosha, but one that is ideal for work. Xosha sat in a room in an inn alone. She looked at the palms of her hands and rubbed them thoughtfully. Work, meaning killing for contract, HER work. She turned the words and with them the deeds over and over in her mind. She could recall thier deaths, everyone one of the victims she had taken for money. That hot blood running down her hands, redness all places. She recalled the color and sent of it. More than once she had lowered her mouth to drink in it, the dying one looking at her in horror but too weak to act against her. <br>
<br>
Xosha put her hands over her face. This face that had loved. This unholy body that had cared for humans. It was no salvation that there was only one or that the one was a woman and only a friend. Was there a difference between that love of a man and a woman, and the love of two friends? She felt that pang in her chest. Try as she might to confuse her emotions, to blanket them with death, with payed murder, there seemed always that painful white ball in her chest. She knew the word for it, though the act of saying it was out of the question Xosha moved her mouth slowly, pronouncing the letters and syllables. <br>
<br>
She put her fingers to her mouth, felt how they curved and pursed, and then clenched and released. Love.. her fingers felt the sensation from her face. It didn't hurt to think about it. She tried again, moving her lips silently. the same dull ache throbbed in her chest, but didn't get larger or hurt her more as she had feared it might. <br>
<br>
Xosha's lips moved again, this time the tiniest rasp of a whisper in the back of her throat emerged. She held her fingers to her mouth still. &quot;....lu...vuh....&quot; <br>
<br>
At that moment a knock on the door across for hers in this poor Inn within Qeynos shocked Xosha into standing. Her heart beat and guilt washed over her. She panted and looked at the door, as if she could pierce through it. Irrationally she thought to herself, had they heard her? <br>
<br>
There was a reply and the knock was greated with a door opening and a friendly greeting, then the door closing, and silence again. Ashamed of herself Xosha sat back down. Her eyes distant, she began to gear up. As she stared, she dressed herself, her face like a worn sheet. <br>
<br>
After she was dressed, Xosha opened her door and walked out, with a second thought she softly brushed her lips with her gloved fingers. For a momemt she had feared they might have changed, or been injured. Love in a Tier'Dal, it was more than forbidden, it was death for sure. <br>
<br>
And that is why Xosha promptly walked to the sewers, found a human beggar there, disembowled the man, bathed in his inards, methotically ate his heart, painted herself in his blood, and began to dedicate this death to Innoruuk. <br>
<br>
All better, she thought... <br>
<br>
She proceeded to meet Jracol outside the town. The dark elf had information she wanted... <br>
